questionTemplates.text:
M: Mary, do you know anything about this author's latest best-seller?
W: Sure. I've just finished it. I strongly recommend it.
{a}

W: How many students took the IELTS test last month?
M: Well, let me see. Xixty had registered, but not everyone turned up. I believe we had 23 from Korea and 19 from Japan.
{a}

M: I just got a statement from the bank. It says I've drawn $ 300 more than I have in my account.
W: Well, we did spend a lot on our vocation. In fact, we didn't know exactly how much was in our bank.
{a}

W: Where are my reading glasses?
M: Look, they are right over there, on the coffee table.
{a}

M: Good news, I'm not going to have surgery after all. The doctor says I can start working out again soon and maybe play football like before in a few weeks.
W: That's terrific. It would be great if you could get back in shape in time for the World Cup.
{a}

F: I'm going to the Shanghai Grand Theatre. Where shall I get off?
M: At the next stop.
{a}

W: Excuse me. Could you tell me when the next train to Manchester leaves?
M: Sure. Well, it's three now. The next train to Manchester leaves in two hours. But you can take the train to Leeds, which leaves in fifteen minutes and then get off at Manchester, because it stops at Manchester on the way.
{a}

W: How are you,Brandon?
M: Oh,dear,my back's killing me.
{a}

M: Jenny, there's an opening for an assistant manager in our company. You should give it a try.
W: Thank you George, but I've decided to travel a bit before finding another job.
{a}

M: What do you think of the final exam?
W: I thought it would be easy, but at the end of the first hour, I was still on the first page. I hardly had time to get to the last page.
{a}

W: I'm afraid we are going to miss the 3-o'clock train.
M: Don't worry. We can get our tickets changed for this evening.
{a}

W: Rod must be in a bad mood today. What's wrong with him?
M: He was passed over in the selection process for the dean of the admissions office. He'd been hoping for the position for a long time.
{a}

M: Shouldn't we invite Kathy to the party tonight?
W: Invite Kathy? She is the one who is planning the whole thing.
{a}

M: You'll need 36 credit hours to get an M. A. degree. Fifteen must be from the English Department and fifteen from the Education Department. For the remaining six credit hours, you can either write a thesis or take two more selected courses.
W: Right now, this is very confusing to me, but I'm sure I'll know what to do as I learn more about it.
{a}

F: What's for breakfast, Dad?
M: Bread, eggs and milk.
{a}

M: I exhausted I stayed up the whole night studying for my middle term matches exam.
W: But why do you always wait until the last minute?
{a}

F: Well, I'm afraid we haven't got any camera cheaper than this one.
M: Well... thank you for your help. I'll think about it.
{a}

M: It's raining again.
W: It has rained for 4 days. Do you think it'll ever stop?
{a}

W: What are your plans for the future?
M: My dream is to open my own business after I graduate.
{a}

W: Are you busy on Tuesday night, Tom?
M: Well... Uh... I haven't got any definite plans yet. Why?
{a}

W: I think you should accept the job.
M: The company is too far away from my home.
{a}

W: Is John angry?
M: I don't think so. If he were, he'd tell us.
{a}

W: Good morning, sir. Can I help you?
M: Yes. I'd like to buy a chair.
{a}
